76561197996136667,Recommended,302970,29869366,Posted: 12 February,all,SWCarter,"Radiant Defense is a tower defense game.  Its missions are played on a grid.  Enemies get one or more starting points, and they have to make their way to the ending point.  Towers have to be placed on modules, and while there are fixed modules for each mission, you're also allowed to put some down yourself, which means you're allowed to change the route of the enemies.There are about a dozen different towers, including machine guns, laser guns, sniper rifles, and tesla towers.  There are also super weapons, which are more expensive than regular towers but have much better attacks.  Regular towers can be upgraded four times during missions.  There isn't any upgrading outside the missions.There are also a dozen or more types of enemies.  They can be fast; they can be shielded; they can spawn more enemies; they can be resistant to some of your towers; and more.  The in-game information isn't great, so you have to learn by playing and trying things out.The missions in the game tend to be long.  Most have over 30 waves, and the peak is somewhere around 70.  Luckily, you get a save before each wave, so if one goes badly then you can load and try again.  This is friendly but also necessary because your score for each mission depends on how much money you have unused at the end of each wave.  So your goal is to kill everything while spending as little money as possible, which adds a little extra strategy.Overall, Radiant Defense is a pretty vanilla, but it works well enough, especially for the price.  It doesn't do anything new or innovative, but it's colorful and humorous, and it took me over 30 hours to beat the 15-mission campaign plus earn all of the achievements.  The campaign starts out very easy but then gets tough at the end, so don't give up on it after only an hour or two."
,Not Recommended,302970,33497052,Posted: 13 July,all,Tman,"The first 10 or so levels are pretty decent. A lot to like in a TD game, with a lot of variety in waves, the auto-save feature in between waves so you can retry a wave if something slips through, a variety of towers to make you think about how to do it, etc.There are some annoying things - towers turn so slowly; waves are not repeatable meaning you can just redo a wave exactly the same way & you'll get different results; fast forward seems to exacerbate this.But then it introduces what I affectionately term ""the meatshield boss"" which invalidates any pathing / tower variety / etc you might have employed. You basically have to find and retry (or go watch some replays to get a strategy) to use a minimalist setup with your wide variety of towers so you can plunk down 10 missile towers, because nothing is going to work at all against the final 5 or so bosses except missiles.Having to restart a level from the beginning because you can't handle the final boss is just stupid design. And only having one real weapon to combat these bosses takes away the entire point of having all these variety of towers."
